The economic feasibility study from 2001 was based on the assumption that the section near the border and the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains will go under traffic at the same time.
At the time of the examination, it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Highlands would not be opened at the original date.
This reduces the above-mentioned eirr values.
As at 31 December 2005, the cost of both sections was €897 million excluding VAT, which is 27.4% higher than in the 2001 economic analysis.
In addition, there is a risk that Section 0805 will have another more elaborate line of lines, which would affect the cost-effectiveness of the project.
The economic analysis showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically justified with a daily traffic of at least 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010. The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22,940 vehicles per day.
However, a study of diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Central Mountains is based on a traffic volume of 12 600 to 13 750 vehicles per day in 2007, which is below the economic limit.
Increased traffic on the routes intended to replace the missing section with the Bohemian Highlands is likely to result in traffic jams and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the original economic assessment.
The aforementioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low eirr for the construction of the border section of the D 8 will not be achieved.
The construction of the border section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomical.
The construction of the A 17 also resulted in cost increases, as was the case with the construction of the two sections of the D 8 mentioned above.
As part of the overall economic assessment for the 1992 Federal Transport Infrastructure Plan, the Federal Ministry of Transport assumed investment costs of around €320 million.
It thus calculated a benefit / cost ratio of 4.6.
In the meantime, the costs have increased to around €670 million and the benefit / cost ratio has been reduced by more than half.
Regardless of the parallel tests with the nkú, the BRH tested the cost-effectiveness of the planning and construction of the A 17 motorway between 2003 and 2005.
In doing so, he noted that the authority responsible for the approval requested an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A 17.
The BRH managed to convince the Federal Ministry and the Roads Administration of the superfluous nature of the landscape tunnel during the course of the test.
This has prevented €10 million in construction costs and €150 000 in annual operating costs.
During the examination of the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction work was inadequately prepared.
The following example illustrates this:
During the planning phase, the road administration waived the condition of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschen wall, as it was difficult to access.
Only when the tunnel propulsion reached the wall did it catch up.
It was revealed that the rock was more weathered than was assumed in the tender.
Elaborate measures such as anchoring, injections and rock impact protection nets for around €3.3 million were necessary.
The Road Works Administration not only paid the costs for additional services, which are already required, such as securing the Dölzschen wall, but also for those that would not have been necessary in the event of a perfect construction preparation.
These include expenses as a result of disrupted construction processes (€3.2 million), additional training for the propulsion team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of construction time (€7 million).
This additional expenditure of around €10.7 million is not matched by any lasting added value.
The BRH took these and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to better exercise the specialist supervision of major road construction measures that it is responsible for.
In this context, it should insist that the road authorities introduce quality assurance systems.
The benefits of cooperation for BRH and nkú The Cooperation met the expectations of both courts of auditors.
The BRH received insights into the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.
Both courts of auditors have developed a database of bridge and tunnel prices, which will be helpful in future audits.
The ncú found that the most important structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and carriageway of the D 8 are not different from those of the A 17.
The auditors of both audit institutions involved in the cooperation gained valuable experience which will be useful in future audits.
